pirituality more common to sixteenth-century poetry, especially as portrayed by the Petrarchan tradition. Throughclose examination of Aldana's lyric -religious, philosophical, pastoral, and mythological- this study reveals how Aldana exploits the gaps in Petrarchism, Neoplatonism, and contemporary poetic models to communicate his belief inthe importance of the physical in our search for those fleeting moments of transcendental bliss on the earthly plane. Paul Joseph Lennon is Lecturer in Spanish and Comparative Literature at the University of St Andrews,UK.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLove in literature. 0aNeoplatonism in literature. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aBelief.  aDesire.  aFrancisco de Aldana.  aLove Poetry.  aNeoplatonism.  aPetrarchism.  aPhysical Love.  aPhysical.  aRomance.  aSearch.  aSixteenth-Century Poetry.  aSpanish Golden Age.  aSpiritual Love.  aTranscendental Bliss.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787446014?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787446014423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787446014/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles